image.altText: A smiling young blonde woman with a drink in her hand sits in the sun.

props.synopsis: Lachlan Young, 21, has faced a packed courtroom in Ballarat. He is charged with the murder of 23-year-old Hannah McGuire, whose body was found in a burnt-out car last week.

title.children: Man accused of murdering Hannah McGuire faces court in Ballarat

image.altText: A woman smiling and taking a selfie

props.synopsis: The alleged murder of a woman whose body was found in a burnt-out car near Ballarat last week reignites calls to prevent violence against women and create a culture of respect and equality.

title.children: Anti-violence advocate labels alleged murder of 23-year-old Clunes woman Hannah McGuire a 'national tragedy'

image.altText: Eva Lawler at an indoor press conference with flags in the background.

props.synopsis: The NT government announces the youth curfew in Alice Springs, initially ordered for two weeks, will be extended by six nights.

title.children: Youth curfew in Alice Springs will be extended by six nights

image.altText: A graphic of a thermometer and the globe indicating rising heat

props.synopsis: As the world continues its spell of hottest months on record, leading climate scientists say there is a margin to the persistent heat which cannot be explained by the effects of known climate drivers and global warming.

title.children: 'Uncharted territory': The world's extreme heat can't be fully explained, and scientists are worried

image.altText: Anthony Albanese at a press conference.

props.synopsis: Australia's Prime Minister Anthony Albanese urges his Israeli counterpart to avoid a ground invasion of Rafah in southern Gaza, after Benjamin Netanyahu flagged a date had been set for the offensive.

title.children: Albanese urges Netanyahu to avoid Rafah invasion, questions why Gaza aid has taken so long

image.altText: A transgender woman walks past photographs outside a court house.

props.synopsis: Social media platform Giggle for Girls is being sued by transgender woman Roxanne Tickle after her access to the women-only app was revoked. The app's owner has denied Ms Tickle is a woman.

title.children: Transgender woman sues women-only social media platform she was excluded from

image.altText: Back of grey-haired woman's head at desk with computer screen and take-away coffee cup

props.synopsis: New analysis from KPMG shows how COVID has pushed more people over 55 back into the workforce, with the retirement age steadily increasing over the past 20 years.

title.children: The average retirement age is going up, and young people entering the workforce may be working until 70

image.altText: Photo of two mobile phones in people's hands

props.synopsis: Australians are on track for a government-issued digital ID. Most people seem relaxed, but it's the number one story on "alt social media".

title.children: Spooky theories on the big-bad-almost hack and an ugly window into the world of 'alt social media'

image.altText: Customers stand near the entrance of a shoe store called Vern's in a modern shopping mall

props.synopsis: Police confiscate more than 1,100 shoes across Malaysia ahead of the end of Ramadan after an outcry over the footwear's logo that resembles the word "Allah" in Arabic script.

title.children: 'Design flaws': Malaysian shoes with logo resembling Arabic word for God seized during Ramadan

image.altText: A woman with short dark hair inspects cannabis plants on a farm.

image.altText: A man and a woman stand on a beach with their arms around each other. They have grave expressions on their faces.

image.altText: NSW Premier Chris Minns stands at press conference with Police Minister Yasmin Catley and NSW Police Commissioner Karen Webb

props.synopsis: Chris Minns announces a review into termination payouts for public servants after it was revealed $687,613 in "termination payments" has been paid to three former NSW Police chief media advisers in the past two years.

title.children: Termination payouts to NSW police media advisers totalling almost $690k prompts review

image.altText: Yellow 'DANGER ASBESTOS DUST HAZARD' tape in front of a playground with a metal slide and gate.

props.synopsis: Small pieces of asbestos-contaminated mulch have been popping up in a handful of Melbourne parks. But is there any real cause for alarm?

image.altText: Marles and a man in navy uniform stand in a courtyard, an Australian flag behind them.

image.altText: A middle-aged man with receding hair and beard, wearing a singlet and glasses.

props.synopsis: Aliyawar Yawari had been charged with two counts of indecently assaulting a female guest at an Adelaide motel, however the charges will no longer proceed.

image.altText: Benjamin Netanyahu wearing suit stands in front of flag of Israel

image.altText: A woman with long brown hair stares directly in to a camera with a Palestinian flag behind her.

image.altText: A girl with scabs and bruises on her forehead is hugged by a women in a black and white headscarf

image.altText: Matildas coach Tony Gustavsson scratches his head while speaking to media at a press conference

image.altText: A concept image of Toondah Harbour

image.altText: An X-ray printout showing a pelvis with two hips replaced.

image.altText: Bespectacled woman with brown hair and yellow top sitting standing in front of new smart power meter

image.altText: A submarine with a red, white and blue flag on the front sits on an empty patch of concrete

image.altText: A man and woman hugging in front of a for sale sign at a house

image.altText: A man wearing special glasses over his eyes.

image.altText: Man in military uniform.

image.altText: Ella Mason poses for a photo with a medicine ball on their shoulder, at Pony Club Gym in Melbourne.

image.altText: Two women look at a share price board outside the ASX in Sydney.

image.altText: A close up of a Bellinger River turtle face
